In this lecture, I'm going to give you an exercise.

2
00:00:03.510 --> 00:00:08.930
Thus far, you've had the opportunity to view my process for developing themes.

3
00:00:08.940 --> 00:00:12.750
Hopefully you've been following along with me for this lecture.

4
00:00:12.750 --> 00:00:14.910
I'm going to give you an exercise.

5
00:00:14.910 --> 00:00:18.120
The last section in our template is the footer.

6
00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:20.250
Let's take a look at the footer.

7
00:00:20.250 --> 00:00:23.610
Looking closely, the footer has a few sections.

8
00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:30.660
First, we have a set of three columns with headings and paragraphs afterward there's a white line that

9
00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:32.340
goes straight through the footer.

10
00:00:32.340 --> 00:00:35.340
We haven't explored all of WordPress blocks.

11
00:00:35.340 --> 00:00:40.350
However, there is a block for adding a separator below the separator.

12
00:00:40.350 --> 00:00:43.800
There's another paragraph of text on the right side.

13
00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:45.990
There are social media links.

14
00:00:45.990 --> 00:00:49.860
WordPress has a block for creating this type of UI.

15
00:00:49.890 --> 00:00:55.410
Overall, we don't need HTML blocks for creating a footer at this point.

16
00:00:55.410 --> 00:01:00.210
I feel like you can tackle this type of template on your own as an exercise.

17
00:01:00.210 --> 00:01:06.090
Try recreating the footer with blocks, take your time and don't worry about being perfect.

18
00:01:06.090 --> 00:01:10.860
We'll go through the solution together, pause the video and good luck.

19
00:01:11.610 --> 00:01:12.640
Welcome back.

20
00:01:12.660 --> 00:01:16.580
If you were able to successfully create the template, that's great.

21
00:01:16.590 --> 00:01:18.170
If not, that's fine.

22
